Hi everyone,

as we are using some kind of "use-counts" of our textures we are reliant of calling the dispose of an object only once.

Unfortunately the mChildren-Vector in the DisplayObjectContainer will not be resetted in the dispose - so (under some wired conditions) the for - loop will trigger the dispose of the children twice (or even more)...

Do you see any problems in resetting the vector after the work is done? For me somthing like the following works fine - but I would like to prevent any side effects:

``` as3
public override function dispose(): void {
    for (var i: int = mChildren.length - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
        mChildren[i].dispose();
    }
    super.dispose();

    //reset the vector to prevent duplicate dispose-calls
    mChildren.length = 0;
}


Thanks a lot!
```

Hi 
My colleague Moreno and I looked at the code of removeFromParent and saw that it simply does this:

```
    if (mParent) mParent.removeChild(this, dispose);
```

wouldn't it be better that if there ISN'T a parent IT DISPOSES the element ANYWAY?
Like this:

```
    if (mParent) {
    mParent.removeChild(this, dispose);
} else if (dispose) {
    this.dispose();
}
```

What do you think?
tks ^_^
